quran[7]{c,v,t,f}:
34,1,"All praise be to Allah to Whom belongs all that is in the heavens and all that is in the earth, {1} and all praise be to Him in the World to Come. {2} He is Most Wise, All-Aware. {3}",footnotes:1:The Arabic word hamd is used both for praise and for gratitude and both the meanings are implied here. When Allah alone is the Owner of the whole universe and of everything in it
34,2,"He knows what penetrates into the earth and what goes forth from it, what descends from the heaven and what ascends to it. He is the Most Merciful, the Most Forgiving. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
34,3,"The unbelievers say: “How come the Hour is not coming upon us!” {1} Say to them: “Yes indeed, by my Lord, by Him Who fully knows the realm beyond the ken of perception, that the Hour shall inevitably come upon you. {2} Nothing escapes Him, not even the smallest particle in the heavens or the earth; nor is anything smaller or bigger than that but is in a Manifest Book.” {3}",footnotes:1:This they said satirically and mockingly. What they meant was: “This Prophet (peace be upon him) has been giving us the news of his coming of Resurrection for along time now
34,4,"(The Hour shall come) that He may reward those who believe and do righteous deeds. Theirs shall be forgiveness and a generous provision."
34,5,"As for those who worked against Our Signs in order to frustrate them, they shall suffer a painful chastisement. {1}",footnotes:1:The above was an argument for the possibility of the Hereafter: this is an argument for its need and necessity. It means: A time must come when the wicked should be requited for their wickedness and the righteous rewarded for their righteousness. Reason wants and justice demands that a worker of goodness should be rewarded and a worker of evil punished. Now when you see that in the present worldly life neither is an evildoer fully requited for his evil nor a worker of goodness for his goodness
34,6,"(O Prophet), those who have knowledge see clearly that what has been revealed to you from your Lord is the Truth and directs to the Way of the Most Mighty, the Immensely Praiseworthy Lord. {1}",footnotes:1:That is
34,7,"The unbelievers say: “Shall we direct you to the man who tells you that when you have been utterly broken to pieces, you will be raised to life again?"
